Two separate problems, two targeted fixes:

## 1. Out-of-order messages

Kafka guarantees order **within a partition**. If you're seeing out-of-order delivery, your messages that need ordering are landing in different partitions.

**Fix:** Set a partition key on related messages so they always hit the same partition.

```java
// Before: round-robin across partitions
producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("orders", event.toBytes()));

// After: all events for the same order go to the same partition
producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("orders", order.getId(), event.toBytes()));
```

That's it. Same order ID = same partition = guaranteed order. Pick whatever your natural ordering entity is (order ID, user ID, account ID, etc.).

Also check `max.in.flight.requests.per.connection` on your producer. If it's >1 and retries are enabled, batches can arrive out of order. Either set it to `1`, or (better) enable idempotency which handles this for you:

```properties
enable.idempotence=true
```

## 2. Duplicate processing

This is the at-least-once delivery problem. Consumer crashes after processing but before committing the offset, rebalance happens, message gets redelivered.

**Minimal fix: idempotent consumers.** Make your processing a no-op if it's already been applied.

```java
// Option A: Database-level dedup with a unique constraint
try {
    db.execute("""
        INSERT INTO processed_events (event_id, result, processed_at)
        VALUES (?, ?, NOW())
        """, event.getId(), result);
    // First time - process it
    offsetCommit();
} catch (DuplicateKeyException e) {
    // Already processed - skip, commit offset, move on
    log.info("Skipping duplicate event {}", event.getId());
    offsetCommit();
}

// Option B: If your processing is a DB write, make IT idempotent
// Use upserts instead of inserts
db.execute("""
    INSERT INTO orders (id, status, updated_at)
    VALUES (?, ?, NOW())
    ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET status = ?, updated_at = NOW()
    """, order.getId(), newStatus, newStatus);
```

Option A needs your events to carry a unique ID (they should already). Option B works when the downstream write is naturally idempotent.

## Which to pick

| Situation | Approach |
|---|---|
| Events have unique IDs | Dedup table with unique constraint |
| Processing is a DB upsert | Make the write itself idempotent |
| Both | Belt and suspenders, do both |

## What NOT to do

- Don't reach for exactly-once semantics (`isolation.level=read_committed` + transactional producers) unless you're doing Kafka-to-Kafka pipelines. It's a much bigger change and doesn't help when the sink is an external DB.
- Don't add a Redis dedup cache as a first move - it's another failure domain. Your DB already has unique constraints, use them.
- Don't reduce consumer parallelism to "fix" ordering - fix the partition key instead.

The two fixes are independent and each is a few lines of code. Partition keys for ordering, idempotent writes for dedup. No rearchitecting needed.

Algebraic data types (sum types / discriminated unions).

Most developers live in a world of classes, interfaces, and nullable fields where invalid states are *representable*. Sum types flip that: you make illegal states unrepresentable at the type level.

```typescript
// The common approach - stringly typed, easy to mess up
type Order = {
  status: string          // "pending" | "shipped" | "delivered" | ???
  trackingNumber?: string // required when shipped, but nothing enforces that
  deliveredAt?: Date      // same problem
}

// With discriminated unions - invalid states can't exist
type Order =
  | { status: "pending" }
  | { status: "shipped"; trackingNumber: string }
  | { status: "delivered"; trackingNumber: string; deliveredAt: Date }
```

Now you literally *cannot* have a shipped order without a tracking number. The compiler catches it, not a runtime check buried in some validation layer.

**Why it's underrated:**

- **Eliminates entire categories of bugs.** No more "wait, can this field be null here?" - the type tells you exactly what shape you're working with.
- **Exhaustiveness checking.** Add a new variant and the compiler shows you every switch/match that needs updating. Try that with an enum and a bunch of if-else chains.
- **Self-documenting.** The type *is* the documentation of valid states. No need for a comment explaining which field combinations are legal.

**Why developers skip it:**

Most people learn OOP first and reach for inheritance/polymorphism by default. Languages like Java and Go didn't have proper sum types until recently (sealed interfaces, sort of). And TypeScript has them but most tutorials teach interfaces-and-optional-fields instead.

Rust and F# developers get this for free and wonder how everyone else lives without it. They're right to wonder.
